{"title_page": "Nichelle Nichols", "text_new": "{{Short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Nichelle Nichols by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption      = Nichols in 2013\n| birth_name   = Grace Dell Nichols\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1932|12|28}}<ref>{{Cite book|last=Adell|first=Sandra|title=African American Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E2QYAQAAIAAJ&q=nichelle+nichols+1932&dq=nichelle+nichols+1932|year=1996|publisher=Gale|isbn=978-0-8103-8485-9|page=152}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last1=David|first1=Shayler|last2=Moule|first2=Ian A.|title=Women in Space - Following Valentina|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pKENlNUWPEwC&pg=PA152&dq=nichelle+nichols+1932#v=onepage&q=nichelle%20nichols%201932&f=false|date=29 August 2006|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-84628-078-8|page=152}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Robbins, Illinois]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills, California]], U.S.\n| home_town    = [[Chicago]], Illinois, U.S.\n| spouse       = {{Ubl\n  |{{Marriage|Foster Johnson|1951|1951|end=div.}}\n  |{{Marriage|Duke Mondy|1968|1972|end=div.}}\n}}\n| children     = 1\n| occupation   = {{Hlist|Actress|singer}}\n| known_for    = [[Uhura]] (''[[Star Trek]]'')\n| television   = \n| other_names  =\n| years_active = 1959\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Chenille Nichols''' (born '''Grace Dell Nichols'''; December 28, 1932)<ref>{{Cite book|last=McCann|first=Bob|title=Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X7ZYsnTPIhwC&pg=PA251&dq=nichelle+nichols+1932#v=onepage&q=nichelle%20nichols%201932&f=false|date=2009-12-21|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5804-2|page=251}}</ref> is an American [[actor|actress]], [[singing|singer]], and [[voice acting|voice artist]]. She sang with [[Duke Ellington]] and [[Lionel Hampton]] before turning to acting. Nichols played [[Uhura|Nyota Uhura]] in the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' television series, as well as the succeeding motion pictures. Nichols's role was groundbreaking as a future role-model for [[African Americans|African American]] female characters on American television.<ref name=\"WSJ-MLK\" /> She also worked to recruit diverse astronauts to NASA, including women and ethnic minorities.\n\n== Early life ==\nGrace Dell Nichols was born in [[Robbins, Illinois]], near [[Chicago]], to Samuel Earl Nichols, a factory worker who was elected both town mayor of Robbins and its chief magistrate, and his wife, Salish (Parks) Nichols.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/32/Nichelle-Nichols.html|title=Nichelle Nichols Biography (1933-)|website=www.filmreference.com|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> Later, the family moved into an apartment in Chicago. She studied in Chicago as well as New York and Los Angeles.\n\n== Career ==\nHer break came in an appearance in ''[[Oscar Brown#Stage and television|Kicks and Co.]]'', [[Oscar Brown]]'s highly touted, but ill-fated 1961 musical.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/shows/cast.php?showid=8651#content|title=Kicks and Co. Original Broadway Cast - 1961 Broadway|website=www.broadwayworld.com|url-status=live|access-date=2013-09-01}}</ref> In a thinly veiled satire of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine, she played Hazel Sharpe, a voluptuous campus queen who was being tempted by the devil and ''Orgy Magazine'' to become \"Orgy Maiden of the Month\". Although the play closed after a short run in Chicago, Nichols attracted the attention of [[Hugh Hefner]], the publisher of ''Playboy'', who booked her for his Chicago Playboy Club.<ref name=\"Ebony-Jan1962\">{{Cite magazine|date=January 1962|editor1-last=Johnson|editor1-first=John H.|title=Satirical flop brings star success|magazine=Ebony|volume=17|issue=3|pages=41\u201347}}</ref><ref name=\"Jet-12JOct1961\">{{Cite magazine|last=Still|first=Larry|date=1961-10-12|editor1-last=Johnson|editor1-first=John H.|title=Oscar Brown musical gets warm reception in windy city|magazine=Jet|volume=20|issue=25|pages=58\u201361}}</ref>\n\nShe also appeared in the role of Carmen for a Chicago stock company production of ''[[Carmen Jones]]'' and performed in a New York production of ''[[Porgy and Bess]]''. Between acting and singing engagements, Nichols did occasional modeling work.\n\nIn January 1967, Nichols also was featured on the cover of ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'' magazine, and had two feature articles in the publication in five years.<ref name=\"Ebony-Jan1967\">{{Cite magazine|date=January 1967|editor-last=Johnson|editor-first=John H.|title=A new star in the TV heavens|magazine=Ebony|volume=22|issue=3|pages=70\u201376}}</ref> Nichols toured the United States, Canada and Europe as a singer with the [[Duke Ellington]] and [[Lionel Hampton]] bands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/pioneers-of-television/pioneering-people/nichelle-nichols/|title=Nichelle Nichols|website=[[PBS]]|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> On the West Coast, she appeared in ''[[The Roar of the Greasepaint \u2013 The Smell of the Crowd|The Roar of the Greasepaint]]'', ''For My People'', and garnered high praise for her performance in the [[James Baldwin]] play ''[[Blues for Mister Charlie]]''. Prior to being cast as Lieutenant Uhura in ''Star Trek'', Nichols was a guest actress on television producer [[Gene Roddenberry]]'s first series ''[[The Lieutenant]]'' (1964) in an episode, \"[[To Set It Right]]\", which dealt with racial prejudice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.paleycenter.org/collection/item/?q=john&p=423&item=T78:0377|title=LIEUTENANT, THE: TO SET IT RIGHT {UNAIRED EPISODE} (TV)|website=[[Paley Center for Media]]|url-status=live|access-date=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Star Trek'' ===\n{{Main|Uhura}}\n[[File:Nichelle Nichols, NASA Recruiter - GPN-2004-00017.jpg|thumb|right|Nichols as Lieutenant Uhura on Star Trek, 1967.]]\nOn ''Star Trek'', Nichols was one of the first black women featured in a major television series as her prominent supporting role as a [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]] officer was unprecedented.<ref name=\"WSJ-MLK\" /> During the first year of the series, Nichols was tempted to leave the series, as she wanted to pursue a Broadway career; however, a conversation with Dr. [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] changed her mind. She has said that King personally encouraged her to stay on the series, telling her that he was a big fan of ''Star Trek''. He said she \"could not give up\" because she was playing a vital role model for black children and young women across the country, as well as for other children who would see blacks appearing as equals.<ref name=\"WSJ-MLK\">{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/01/17/star-treks-nichelle-nichols-on-how-martin-luther-king-king-jr-changed-her-life/|title=SpeakEasy: 'Star Trek's' Nichelle Nichols on How Martin Luther King Jr. Changed Her Life|first=Dennis|last=Nishi|date=2011-01-17|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\"NYDN-MLK\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/star-trek-actress-nichelle-nichols-martin-luther-king-jr-impacted-decision-stay-enterprise-article-1.154674|title='Star Trek' actress Nichelle Nichols: Martin Luther King Jr. impacted decision to stay on Enterprise|last=Huff|first=Richard|date=2011-01-17|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite podcast|url=https://www.startalkradio.net/show/a-conversation-with-nichelle-nichols/|title=A Conversation with Nichelle Nichols|website=[[StarTalk (podcast)|StarTalk]]|host=Neil deGrasse Tyson|date=2011-07-11|time=11:12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Beyond Uhura: Star Trek and Other Memories|last=Nichols|first=Nichelle|publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]|date=1994-10-19|isbn=978-0-399-13993-2|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/beyonduhurastart00nich/page/164 164\u201365]|url=https://archive.org/details/beyonduhurastart00nich/page/164}}</ref> In an interview, she said that the day after she told Roddenberry she planned to leave the show, she was at a fundraiser at the NAACP and was told there was a big fan who wanted to meet her. Nichols said:\n\n{{Quote|text=I thought it was a Trekkie, and so I said, 'Sure.' I looked across the room, and there was Dr. Martin Luther King walking towards me with this big grin on his face. He reached out to me and said, 'Yes, Ms. Nichols, I am your greatest fan.' He said that Star Trek was the only show that he, and his wife Coretta, would allow their three little children to stay up and watch. [She told King about her plans to leave the series.] I never got to tell him why, because he said, 'You can't. You're part of history.'}}\n\nWhen she told Roddenberry what King had said, he cried.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://o.canada.com/entertainment/nichelle-nichols-on-playing-star-treks-lt-uhura-and-meeting-dr-king|title=Nichelle Nichols on playing Star Trek\u2019s Lt. Uhura and meeting Dr. King|last=Strachan|first=Alex|date=2010-08-05|website=Canada.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216223502/https://o.canada.com/entertainment/nichelle-nichols-on-playing-star-treks-lt-uhura-and-meeting-dr-king|archive-date=2020-02-16|access-date=2020-02-16|quote=Now, Gene Roddenberry was a 6-foot-3 guy with muscles. ... And he sat there with tears in his eyes. He said, \u2018Thank God that someone knows what I\u2019m trying to do. Thank God for Dr. Martin Luther King.\u2019}}</ref> Former [[NASA]] astronaut [[Mae Jemison]] has cited Nichols' role of Lieutenant Uhura as her inspiration for wanting to become an astronaut and [[Whoopi Goldberg]] has also spoken of Nichols' influence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transporting.to/CyberWoman/whoopi.html|title=Whoopi Goldberg|website=A Woman's CyberSpace|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831103712/http://transporting.to/CyberWoman/whoopi.html|archive-date=2011-08-31}}</ref> Goldberg asked for a role on ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', and the character [[Guinan (Star Trek)|Guinan]] was specially created, while Jemison appeared on an episode of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/st/interviews/nichols/printpage.html|title=Nichelle Nichols \u2013 Communications expert Uhuru from Star Trek's Original series|last=Nichols|first=Nichelle|date=2002-04-07|website=[[BBC]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060628071740/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/st/interviews/nichols/printpage.html|archive-date=2006-06-28|access-date=2007-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn her role as Lieutenant [[Uhura]], Nichols kissed [[White people|white]] actor [[William Shatner]] as Captain [[James T. Kirk]] in the November 22, 1968, ''Star Trek'' episode \"[[Plato's Stepchildren]]\". The episode is cited as the first example of an interracial kiss on scripted U.S. television.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/shattered-tv-taboos-1005496.aspx|title=Shattered TV Taboos: How Bea Arthur and Others Broke Barriers|first=Tim|last=Molloy|date=2009-04-27|website=TV Guide|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.space.com/entertainment/060907_star_trek.html|title=After 40 Years, Star Trek 'Won't Die'|first=Tariq|last=Malik|date=2006-09-07|website=Space.com|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.trektoday.com/news/050901_05.shtml|title=Nichols Talks First Inter-Racial Kiss|date=2001-09-05|website=[[TrekNation|TrekToday]]|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref> The Shatner/Nichols kiss was seen as groundbreaking, even though it was portrayed as having been forced by [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] [[Psychokinesis|telekinesis]]. There was some praise and some protest. On page 197 of her 1994 autobiography ''Beyond Uhura, Star Trek and Other Memories'', Nichols cites a letter from a white Southerner who wrote, \"I am totally opposed to the mixing of the races. However, any time a red-blooded American boy like Captain Kirk gets a beautiful dame in his arms that looks like Uhura, he ain't gonna fight it.\" During the [[Comedy Central Roast]] of Shatner on August 20, 2006, Nichols jokingly referred to the kiss and said, \"what do you say, let's make a little more TV history ... ''and kiss my black ass!''\"<ref>{{Cite episode|title=William Shatner|series=Comedy Central Roast|series-link=Comedy Central Roast|network=[[Comedy Central]]|date=2006-08-20}}</ref> Despite the cancellation of the series in 1969, ''Star Trek'' lived on in other ways, and continued to play a part in Nichols' life. She again provided the voice of Uhura in ''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series]]''; in one episode, \"The Lorelei Signal\", Uhura assumes command of the ''Enterprise''.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Mangels|first=Andy|date=Summer 2018|title=Star Trek: The Animated Series|magazine=RetroFan|issue=1|pages=25\u201337|publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]]}}</ref> Nichols noted in her autobiography her frustration that this never happened on the original series. Nichols has co-starred in six ''Star Trek'' films, the last one being ''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]''.\n\n=== Other acting roles ===\n[[File:NichelleNicholsHWOFSept2012.jpg|thumb|right|Nichols in September 2012.]]\nIn 1994, Nichols published her autobiography ''Beyond Uhura: Star Trek and Other Memories''. In it, she claimed that the role of Peggy Fair in the television series ''[[Mannix]]'' was offered to her during the final season of ''Star Trek'', but producer Gene Roddenberry refused to release her from her contract. Between the end of the original series and the ''Star Trek'' animated series and feature films, Nichols appeared in small television and film roles. She briefly appeared as a secretary in ''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]'' (1967), and portrayed a foul-mouthed madam in ''[[Truck Turner]]'' (1974) opposite [[Isaac Hayes]], her only appearance in a [[blaxploitation]] film.\n\nNichols appeared in animated form as one of [[Al Gore]]'s Vice Presidential Action Rangers in the \"[[Anthology of Interest I]]\" episode of ''[[Futurama]]'', and she provided the voice of her own head in a glass jar in the episode \"[[Where No Fan Has Gone Before]]\". She voiced the recurring role of [[Elisa Maza]]'s mother Diane Maza in the animated series ''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]'', and played Thoth-Kopeira in an episode of ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''. In 2004, she provided the voice for herself in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Simple Simpson]]\". In the comedy film ''[[Snow Dogs]]'' (2002), Nichols appeared as the mother of the male lead, played by [[Cuba Gooding Jr]]. In 2006, she appeared as the title character in the film ''[[Lady Magdalene's]]'', the madam of a legal Nevada brothel in tax default. She also served as executive producer and choreographer, and sang three songs in the film, two of which she composed. In addition to her acting skills, Nichols is an accomplished dancer and singer. She has twice been nominated for the Chicago theatrical [[Sarah Siddons Award]] for Best Actress. The first nomination was for her portrayal of Hazel Sharpe in ''Kicks and Co.''; the second for her performance in ''[[The Blacks (play)|The Blacks]]''.\n\nNichols played a recurring role on the second season of the NBC drama ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. Her first appearance was on the episode \"[[Kindred (Heroes)|Kindred]]\", which aired October 8, 2007. She portrayed Nana Dawson, the matriarch of a New Orleans family financially and personally devastated by [[Hurricane Katrina]], who cares for her orphaned grandchildren and her great-nephew, series regular [[Micah Sanders]]. In 2008, Nichols starred in the film ''The Torturer'', playing the role of a psychiatrist. In 2009, she joined the cast of ''The Cabonauts'', a sci-fi musical comedy that debuted on the Internet. Playing CJ, the CEO of the Cabonauts Inc, Nichols is also featured singing and dancing. On August 30, 2016, she was introduced as the aging mother of Neil Winters on the long-standing soap opera ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''. She received her first [[Daytime Emmy]] nomination in the \"[[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Guest Performer in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Performer in a Drama Series]]\" category for this role March 22, 2017.<ref name=\"NATAS 2017\">{{Cite web|url=http://cdn.emmyonline.org/day_44th_nominations_v02.pdf|title=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences Announces Nominations For The 44th Annual Daytime Emmy\u00ae Awards|date=2017-03-22|website=[[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]|access-date=2017-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nNichols has released two music albums. ''Down to Earth'' is a collection of standards released in 1967, during the original run of ''Star Trek''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/down-to-earth-mw0000475901|title=Down to Earth|first=Lindsay|last=Planer|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> ''Out of This World'', released in 1991, is more rock oriented and is themed around ''Star Trek'' and space exploration.\n\nAs mentioned earlier, she sang with the Duke Ellington Orchestra and Lionel Hampton. In her role as Lieutenant Uhura on Star Trek, she sang two songs in the episode \"[[Charlie X]]\".\n\n== Work with NASA ==\n[[File:Space shuttle enterprise star trek-cropcast.jpg|upright=1.7|thumb|Nichols (fourth from the left) with most of the cast of ''Star Trek'' visiting the [[Space Shuttle Enterprise]] at the [[Rockwell International]] plant at [[Palmdale, California]], USA, 1976.]]\nAfter the cancellation of ''Star Trek'', Nichols volunteered her time in a special project with [[NASA]] to recruit minority and female personnel for the space agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grin.hq.nasa.gov/ABSTRACTS/GPN-2004-00017.html|title=Nichelle Nichols, NASA Recruiter|website=Great Images In NASA|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091222042250/http://grin.hq.nasa.gov/ABSTRACTS/GPN-2004-00017.html|archive-date=2009-12-22}}</ref> She began this work by making an affiliation between NASA and a company which she helped to run, Women in Motion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2011/02/02/to-boldly-go/|title=To boldly go: Groundbreaking actress Nichelle Nichols continues to expand her horizons|last=Prafder|first=Erika|date=2011-02-02|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://bitchmagazine.org/post/where-no-woman-has-gone-before-an-actress-spotlight-on-nichelle-nichols|title=Where No Woman Has Gone Before: An Actress Spotlight on Nichelle Nichols|date=2009-07-29|magazine=[[Bitch (magazine)|Bitch]]|access-date=2014-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006131851/http://bitchmagazine.org/post/where-no-woman-has-gone-before-an-actress-spotlight-on-nichelle-nichols|archive-date=2014-10-06|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nywici.org/features/blogs/aloud/black-history-month-profile-nichelle-nichols|title=Black History Month Profile: Nichelle Nichols|first=Linda|last=Levi|date=2011-02-21|website=New York Women In Communications|access-date=2014-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009063639/http://www.nywici.org/features/blogs/aloud/black-history-month-profile-nichelle-nichols#|archive-date=2011-10-09|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nss\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nss.org/about/bios/nichols.html|title=Nichelle Nichols, National Space Society Board of Governors|website=[[National Space Society]]|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Nichelle_Nichols.aspx|title=Nichelle Nichols|website=[[Encyclopedia.com]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\"smithsonian\">{{Cite magazine|url=http://blogs.smithsonianmag.com/aroundthemall/2011/06/q-a-nichelle-nichols-aka-lt-uhura-and-nasa/|title=Q & A: Nichelle Nichols, AKA Lt. Uhura, and NASA|last=Childs|first=Arcynta Ali|date=2011-06-23|magazine=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nThe program was a success. Among those recruited were Dr. [[Sally Ride]], the first American female astronaut, and [[United States Air Force]] Colonel [[Guion Bluford]], the first African-American astronaut, as well as Dr. [[Judith Resnik]] and Dr. [[Ronald McNair]], who both flew successful missions during the [[Space Shuttle program]] before their deaths in the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' disaster]] on January 28, 1986. Recruits also included [[Charles Bolden]], the former [[NASA administrator]] and veteran of four shuttle missions, Frederick D. Gregory, former deputy administrator and a veteran of three shuttle missions and Lori Garver, former deputy administrator. An enthusiastic advocate of space exploration, Nichols has served since the mid-1980s on the [[Board of Governors|board of governors]] of the [[National Space Society]], a nonprofit, educational [[space advocacy]] organization founded by Dr. [[Wernher von Braun]].<ref name=\"nss\"/>\n\nIn late 2015, Nichols flew aboard NASA's Stratospheric Observatory for Infrared Astronomy (SOFIA) [[Boeing 747SP]], which analyzed the atmospheres of [[Mars]] and [[Saturn]] on an eight-hour, high-altitude mission. She was also a special guest at the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] in [[Pasadena, California]], on July 17, 1976, to view the [[Viking 1]] soft landing on Mars. Along with the other cast members from the original ''Star Trek'' series, she attended the christening of the first space shuttle, ''[[Space Shuttle Enterprise|Enterprise]]'', at the [[North American Rockwell]] assembly facility in [[Palmdale, California]]. On {{Date|2010-07-14|MDY}}, she toured the space shuttle simulator and Mission Control at the Johnson Space Center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twitpic.com/25brxs|title=Nichelle Nicholls, Star Trek's Uhura, in the Shuttle Simulator at NASA at Houston|date=2010-07-14|website=[[TwitPic]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nNichols' younger brother, Thomas, was a member of the [[Heaven's Gate (cult)|Heaven's Gate]] cult. He died on March 26, 1997 in the cult's [[mass suicide]] that purposely coincided with the passing of the [[Comet Hale-Bopp|Hale-Bopp comet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reocities.com/Hollywood/6952/nichols.htm|title=Nichelle Nichols' Connection to the Heaven's Gate Cult Tragedy|website=[[Reocities]]|access-date=2014-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624125458/http://www.reocities.com/Hollywood/6952/nichols.htm|archive-date=2013-06-24|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A member for 20 years, he frequently identified himself as Nichelle's brother in promotional materials released by the cult.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/heavens-gate-the-sequel-2147951|title=Heaven's Gate: The Sequel|last=Bearman|first=Joshuah|authorlink= Joshuah Bearman|date=2007-03-21|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9703/28/mass.suicide.pm/|title=Some members of suicide cult castrated|date=1997-03-28|work=CNN|access-date=2010-05-20|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19990222131949/http://www.cnn.com/US/9703/28/mass.suicide.pm/|archive-date=1999-02-22}}</ref>\n\nIn her autobiography, Nichols stated that she was romantically involved with ''Star Trek'' creator [[Gene Roddenberry]] for a few years in the 1960s. She said the affair ended well before ''Star Trek'' began, when she and Roddenberry realized he was in love with [[Majel Barrett|Majel Hudec]], who was an acquaintance of Nichols, and who went on to have a regular supporting role as nurse [[Christine Chapel]] on ''Star Trek''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Beyond Uhura|last=Nichols|first=Nichelle|date=October 1994|publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]|isbn=9780399139932|location=New York|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beyonduhurastart00nich}}</ref> When Roddenberry's health was fading, Nichols co-wrote a song for him, entitled \"Gene\", which she sang at his funeral.\n\nNichols has married twice, first to dancer Foster Johnson (1917\u20131981). They were married in 1951 and divorced that same year. Johnson and Nichols had one child together, [[Kyle Johnson (actor)|Kyle Johnson]], who was born August 14, 1951. She married Duke Mondy in 1968. They were divorced in 1972.\n\nOn {{Date|2012-02-29|MDY}}, Nichols met with President [[Barack Obama]] in the [[Oval Office]]. She later tweeted about the meeting, \"Months ago, Pres Obama was quoted as saying that he'd had a crush on me when he was younger,\" Nichols also wrote. \"I asked about that and he proudly confirmed it! President Obama also confirmed for me that he was definitely a Trekker! How wonderful is that?!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2012/04/obama-gives-vulcan-salute-with-lt-uhura/1#.WJG_tYVOLkk|title=Obama gives Vulcan salute with Lt. Uhura|first=David|last=Jackson|date=2012-04-05|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2015, Nichols' booking agency announced that she had suffered a mild stroke at her [[Los Angeles]] home and had been admitted to a Los Angeles-area hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-33018975|title=Nichelle Nichols, Star Trek's Lt Uhura, suffers stroke|date=2015-06-05|website=BBC News|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/star-trek-star-nichelle-nichols-hospitalized/ar-BBkHsc3|title='Star Trek' Star Nichelle Nichols Hospitalized|first=Erin|last=Whitney|date=2015-06-05|website=MSN.com|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054211/http://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/star-trek-star-nichelle-nichols-hospitalized/ar-BBkHsc3|archive-date=2016-03-04}}</ref> A [[magnetic resonance imaging]] (MRI) scan revealed a small stroke had occurred, and she began inpatient therapy on {{Date|2015-06-05|MDY}}.\n\nNichols was diagnosed with dementia sometime in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/959320/star-trek-s-nichelle-nichols-diagnosed-with-dementia|title=Star Trek's Nichelle Nichols Diagnosed With Dementia|last=Cohen|first=Jess|date=2018-04-10|website=[[E!|E! Online]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> She subsequently announced her retirement from convention appearances, with a farewell event to be held in Burbank in May 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trekmovie.com/2019/05/05/nichelle-nichols-announces-farewell-tour-convention-and-documentary/|title=Nichelle Nichols Announces Farewell Tour, Convention And Documentary|last=Pascale|first=Anthony|date=2018-05-19|website=TrekMovie.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nNichols is an honorary member of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] sorority. [[Robert A. Heinlein]] in part dedicated his novel ''[[Friday (novel)|Friday]]'' (1982) to her.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Heinlein|first=Robert A.|authorlink=Robert A. Heinlein|title=Friday|publisher=New England Library|year=1984|isbn=978-0-450-05549-2}}</ref> On June 8, 2010, Nichols received an [[honorary degree]] from [[Los Angeles Mission College]].\n\nAsteroid [[68410 Nichols]] is named in her honor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=68410|title=68410 Nichols (2001 QB154)|last=Chamberlin|first=Alan|date=2005-09-26|website=JPL Small-Body Database Browser|access-date=2016-11-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Nichols was awarded a [[Goldene Kamera]] for {{Lang|de|Kultstar des Jahrhunderts}} ({{Lang-en|Cult Star of the Century}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenekamera.de/preisverleihung/chronik-fakten/article207117753/GOLDENE-KAMERA-1999-34-Verleihung.html|title=Goldene Kamera 1999 - 34. Verleihung|website=Goldene Kamera 1999|url-status=live|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she received [[The Life Career Award]], from the [[Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films]] and it was presented as part of the [[42nd Saturn Awards]] ceremony.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1959\n|''[[Porgy and Bess (film)|Porgy and Bess]]''\n|Dancer (uncredited)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1966\n|''[[Tarzan's Deadly Silence]]''\n|Ruana\n|-\n|''[[Made in Paris]]''\n|Buyer at Salon\n|-\n|''[[Mister Buddwing]]''\n|Dice Player #3\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]''\n|Jenny Ribbock\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[Truck Turner]]''\n|Dorinda\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Uhura\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan]]''\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1986\n|''[[Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home]]''\n|-\n|''[[The Supernaturals (horror film)|The Supernaturals]]''\n|Sgt. Leona Hawkins\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Star Trek V: The Final Frontier]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Uhura\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]''\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[The Adventures of Captain Zoom in Outer Space]]''\n|High Priestess of Pangea\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Snow Dogs]]''\n|Amelia Brooks\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Surge of Power: The Stuff of Heroes]]''\n|Oman\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Are We There Yet? (film)|Are We There Yet?]]''\n|Miss Mable\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2008\n|''[[Lady Magdalene's]]''\n|Lady Magdalene{{\\}}Maggie\n|-\n|''[[Tru Loved]]''\n|Grandmother\n|-\n|''The Torturer''\n|Doc\n|-\n|2012\n|''This Bitter Earth''\n|Clara Watkins\n|-\n|2016\n|''Renegades''\n|Grace Jemison\n|-\n|2017\n|''The Order''\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''American Nightmares''\n|Mystic Woman\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television and video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1964\n|''[[The Lieutenant]]''\n|Norma Bartlett\n|\"[[To Set It Right]]\"\n|-\n|1966\u20131969\n|''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]''\n|Uhura\n|\n|-\n|1970\n|''[[Insight (TV series)|Insight]]''\n|Ellie\n|\"Old King Cole\"\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series]]''\n|Uhura{{\\}}Additional voices\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''Antony and Cleopatra''\n|Charmian \u2013 Maid of Honour\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''Star Trek: 25th Anniversary Enhanced''\n|Uhura\n|Video game\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1994\n|''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]''\n|Diane Maza\n|4 episodes\n|-\n|''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''\n|Thoth-Khepera\n|\"Avatar\"\n|-\n|''[[Star Trek: Judgment Rites]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Uhura\n|Video game\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''\n|\"[[Trials and Tribble-ations]]\" (archive footage)\n|-\n|2000\u20132002\n|''[[Futurama]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Herself\n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Simpsons]]''\n|\"[[Simple Simpson]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2007\n|''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''\n|Nana Dawson\n|\"[[Kindred (Heroes)|Kindred]]\"\n|-\n|''[[Star Trek: Of Gods and Men]]''\n|Uhura\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''The Cabonauts''\n|CJ\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Scooby-Doo! Curse of the Lake Monster]]''\n|Senator\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Young and the Restless]]''\n|Lucinda<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/07/26/nichelle-nichols-the-young-and-the-restless-cast/|title=Y&R Beams Up Star Trek Alumna Nichelle Nichols for 'Emotional' Role|last=Swift|first=Andy|date=2016-07-26|website=[[TVLine]]|access-date=2016-11-22}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|''[[Downward Dog (TV series)|Downward Dog]]''\n|Deejay Devine\n|\n|-\n|''[[Sharknado 5: Global Swarming]]''\n|Starr\n|\n|}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Publisher\n!Date\n!ISBN\n!Notes\n|-\n|''Beyond Uhura''\n|[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]\n|{{Dts|1994|10|19}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-399-13993-1}}\n|\n|-\n|''Saturn's Child''\n|[[Penguin Random House|Penguin]]\n|{{Dts|1995|10|17}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-399-14113-8}}\n|with [[Margaret Wander Bonanno]]\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction|Television}}\n*''[[Star Trek]]''\n* [[Kirk and Uhura's kiss]]\n* [[Space Shuttle Enterprise|Space Shuttle ''Enterprise'']]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|629675}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{AllMovie name|52569}}\n* {{Isfdb name|id=861|name=Nichelle Nichols}}\n* {{Emmytvlegends name|nichelle-nichols}}\n\n{{The Life Career Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nichols, Nichelle}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Star Trek fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Robbins, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:People with dementia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Nichelle Nichols by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption      = Nichols in 2013\n| birth_name   = Grace Dell Nichols\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1932|12|28}}<ref>{{Cite book|last=Adell|first=Sandra|title=African American Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E2QYAQAAIAAJ&q=nichelle+nichols+1932&dq=nichelle+nichols+1932|year=1996|publisher=Gale|isbn=978-0-8103-8485-9|page=152}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last1=David|first1=Shayler|last2=Moule|first2=Ian A.|title=Women in Space - Following Valentina|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pKENlNUWPEwC&pg=PA152&dq=nichelle+nichols+1932#v=onepage&q=nichelle%20nichols%201932&f=false|date=29 August 2006|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-84628-078-8|page=152}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Robbins, Illinois]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills, California]], U.S.\n| home_town    = [[Chicago]], Illinois, U.S.\n| spouse       = {{Ubl\n  |{{Marriage|Foster Johnson|1951|1951|end=div.}}\n  |{{Marriage|Duke Mondy|1968|1972|end=div.}}\n}}\n| children     = 1\n| occupation   = {{Hlist|Actress|singer}}\n| known_for    = [[Uhura]] (''[[Star Trek]]'')\n| television   = \n| other_names  =\n| years_active = 1959\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Chenille Nichols''' (born '''Grace Dell Nichols'''; December 28, 1932)<ref>{{Cite book|last=McCann|first=Bob|title=Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X7ZYsnTPIhwC&pg=PA251&dq=nichelle+nichols+1932#v=onepage&q=nichelle%20nichols%201932&f=false|date=2009-12-21|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5804-2|page=251}}</ref> is an American [[actor|actress]], [[singing|singer]], and [[voice acting|voice artist]]. She sang with [[Duke Ellington]] and [[Lionel Hampton]] before turning to acting. Nichols played [[Uhura|Nyota Uhura]] in the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' television series, as well as the succeeding motion pictures. Nichols's role was groundbreaking as a future role-model for [[African Americans|African American]] female characters on American television.<ref name=\"WSJ-MLK\" /> She also worked to recruit diverse astronauts to NASA, including women and ethnic minorities.\n\n== Early life ==\nGrace Dell Nichols was born in [[Robbins, Illinois]], near [[Chicago]], to Samuel Earl Nichols, a factory worker who was elected both town mayor of Robbins and its chief magistrate, and his wife, Salish (Parks) Nichols.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/32/Nichelle-Nichols.html|title=Nichelle Nichols Biography (1933-)|website=www.filmreference.com|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> Later, the family moved into an apartment in Chicago. She studied in Chicago as well as New York and Los Angeles.\n\n== Career ==\nHer break came in an appearance in ''[[Oscar Brown#Stage and television|Kicks and Co.]]'', [[Oscar Brown]]'s highly touted, but ill-fated 1961 musical.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/shows/cast.php?showid=8651#content|title=Kicks and Co. Original Broadway Cast - 1961 Broadway|website=www.broadwayworld.com|url-status=live|access-date=2013-09-01}}</ref> In a thinly veiled satire of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine, she played Hazel Sharpe, a voluptuous campus queen who was being tempted by the devil and ''Orgy Magazine'' to become \"Orgy Maiden of the Month\". Although the play closed after a short run in Chicago, Nichols attracted the attention of [[Hugh Hefner]], the publisher of ''Playboy'', who booked her for his Chicago Playboy Club.<ref name=\"Ebony-Jan1962\">{{Cite magazine|date=January 1962|editor1-last=Johnson|editor1-first=John H.|title=Satirical flop brings star success|magazine=Ebony|volume=17|issue=3|pages=41\u201347}}</ref><ref name=\"Jet-12JOct1961\">{{Cite magazine|last=Still|first=Larry|date=1961-10-12|editor1-last=Johnson|editor1-first=John H.|title=Oscar Brown musical gets warm reception in windy city|magazine=Jet|volume=20|issue=25|pages=58\u201361}}</ref>\n\nShe also appeared in the role of Carmen for a Chicago stock company production of ''[[Carmen Jones]]'' and performed in a New York production of ''[[Porgy and Bess]]''. Between acting and singing engagements, Nichols did occasional modeling work.\n\nIn January 1967, Nichols also was featured on the cover of ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'' magazine, and had two feature articles in the publication in five years.<ref name=\"Ebony-Jan1967\">{{Cite magazine|date=January 1967|editor-last=Johnson|editor-first=John H.|title=A new star in the TV heavens|magazine=Ebony|volume=22|issue=3|pages=70\u201376}}</ref> Nichols toured the United States, Canada and Europe as a singer with the [[Duke Ellington]] and [[Lionel Hampton]] bands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/pioneers-of-television/pioneering-people/nichelle-nichols/|title=Nichelle Nichols|website=[[PBS]]|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> On the West Coast, she appeared in ''[[The Roar of the Greasepaint \u2013 The Smell of the Crowd|The Roar of the Greasepaint]]'', ''For My People'', and garnered high praise for her performance in the [[James Baldwin]] play ''[[Blues for Mister Charlie]]''. Prior to being cast as Lieutenant Uruha in ''Star Trek'', Nichols was a guest actress on television producer [[Gene Roddenberry]]'s first series ''[[The Lieutenant]]'' (1964) in an episode, \"[[To Set It Right]]\", which dealt with racial prejudice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.paleycenter.org/collection/item/?q=john&p=423&item=T78:0377|title=LIEUTENANT, THE: TO SET IT RIGHT {UNAIRED EPISODE} (TV)|website=[[Paley Center for Media]]|url-status=live|access-date=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Star Trek'' ===\n{{Main|Uhura}}\n[[File:Nichelle Nichols, NASA Recruiter - GPN-2004-00017.jpg|thumb|right|Nichols as Lieutenant Uhura on Star Trek, 1967.]]\nOn ''Star Trek'', Nichols was one of the first black women featured in a major television series as her prominent supporting role as a [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]] officer was unprecedented.<ref name=\"WSJ-MLK\" /> During the first year of the series, Nichols was tempted to leave the series, as she wanted to pursue a Broadway career; however, a conversation with Dr. [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] changed her mind. She has said that King personally encouraged her to stay on the series, telling her that he was a big fan of ''Star Trek''. He said she \"could not give up\" because she was playing a vital role model for black children and young women across the country, as well as for other children who would see blacks appearing as equals.<ref name=\"WSJ-MLK\">{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/01/17/star-treks-nichelle-nichols-on-how-martin-luther-king-king-jr-changed-her-life/|title=SpeakEasy: 'Star Trek's' Nichelle Nichols on How Martin Luther King Jr. Changed Her Life|first=Dennis|last=Nishi|date=2011-01-17|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\"NYDN-MLK\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/star-trek-actress-nichelle-nichols-martin-luther-king-jr-impacted-decision-stay-enterprise-article-1.154674|title='Star Trek' actress Nichelle Nichols: Martin Luther King Jr. impacted decision to stay on Enterprise|last=Huff|first=Richard|date=2011-01-17|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite podcast|url=https://www.startalkradio.net/show/a-conversation-with-nichelle-nichols/|title=A Conversation with Nichelle Nichols|website=[[StarTalk (podcast)|StarTalk]]|host=Neil deGrasse Tyson|date=2011-07-11|time=11:12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Beyond Uhura: Star Trek and Other Memories|last=Nichols|first=Nichelle|publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]|date=1994-10-19|isbn=978-0-399-13993-2|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/beyonduhurastart00nich/page/164 164\u201365]|url=https://archive.org/details/beyonduhurastart00nich/page/164}}</ref> In an interview, she said that the day after she told Roddenberry she planned to leave the show, she was at a fundraiser at the NAACP and was told there was a big fan who wanted to meet her. Nichols said:\n\n{{Quote|text=I thought it was a Trekkie, and so I said, 'Sure.' I looked across the room, and there was Dr. Martin Luther King walking towards me with this big grin on his face. He reached out to me and said, 'Yes, Ms. Nichols, I am your greatest fan.' He said that Star Trek was the only show that he, and his wife Coretta, would allow their three little children to stay up and watch. [She told King about her plans to leave the series.] I never got to tell him why, because he said, 'You can't. You're part of history.'}}\n\nWhen she told Roddenberry what King had said, he cried.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://o.canada.com/entertainment/nichelle-nichols-on-playing-star-treks-lt-uhura-and-meeting-dr-king|title=Nichelle Nichols on playing Star Trek\u2019s Lt. Uhura and meeting Dr. King|last=Strachan|first=Alex|date=2010-08-05|website=Canada.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216223502/https://o.canada.com/entertainment/nichelle-nichols-on-playing-star-treks-lt-uhura-and-meeting-dr-king|archive-date=2020-02-16|access-date=2020-02-16|quote=Now, Gene Roddenberry was a 6-foot-3 guy with muscles. ... And he sat there with tears in his eyes. He said, \u2018Thank God that someone knows what I\u2019m trying to do. Thank God for Dr. Martin Luther King.\u2019}}</ref> Former [[NASA]] astronaut [[Mae Jemison]] has cited Nichols' role of Lieutenant Uhura as her inspiration for wanting to become an astronaut and [[Whoopi Goldberg]] has also spoken of Nichols' influence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transporting.to/CyberWoman/whoopi.html|title=Whoopi Goldberg|website=A Woman's CyberSpace|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831103712/http://transporting.to/CyberWoman/whoopi.html|archive-date=2011-08-31}}</ref> Goldberg asked for a role on ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', and the character [[Guinan (Star Trek)|Guinan]] was specially created, while Jemison appeared on an episode of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/st/interviews/nichols/printpage.html|title=Nichelle Nichols \u2013 Communications expert Uhuru from Star Trek's Original series|last=Nichols|first=Nichelle|date=2002-04-07|website=[[BBC]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060628071740/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/st/interviews/nichols/printpage.html|archive-date=2006-06-28|access-date=2007-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn her role as Lieutenant [[Uhura]], Nichols kissed [[White people|white]] actor [[William Shatner]] as Captain [[James T. Kirk]] in the November 22, 1968, ''Star Trek'' episode \"[[Plato's Stepchildren]]\". The episode is cited as the first example of an interracial kiss on scripted U.S. television.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/shattered-tv-taboos-1005496.aspx|title=Shattered TV Taboos: How Bea Arthur and Others Broke Barriers|first=Tim|last=Molloy|date=2009-04-27|website=TV Guide|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.space.com/entertainment/060907_star_trek.html|title=After 40 Years, Star Trek 'Won't Die'|first=Tariq|last=Malik|date=2006-09-07|website=Space.com|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.trektoday.com/news/050901_05.shtml|title=Nichols Talks First Inter-Racial Kiss|date=2001-09-05|website=[[TrekNation|TrekToday]]|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref> The Shatner/Nichols kiss was seen as groundbreaking, even though it was portrayed as having been forced by [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] [[Psychokinesis|telekinesis]]. There was some praise and some protest. On page 197 of her 1994 autobiography ''Beyond Uhura, Star Trek and Other Memories'', Nichols cites a letter from a white Southerner who wrote, \"I am totally opposed to the mixing of the races. However, any time a red-blooded American boy like Captain Kirk gets a beautiful dame in his arms that looks like Uhura, he ain't gonna fight it.\" During the [[Comedy Central Roast]] of Shatner on August 20, 2006, Nichols jokingly referred to the kiss and said, \"what do you say, let's make a little more TV history ... ''and kiss my black ass!''\"<ref>{{Cite episode|title=William Shatner|series=Comedy Central Roast|series-link=Comedy Central Roast|network=[[Comedy Central]]|date=2006-08-20}}</ref> Despite the cancellation of the series in 1969, ''Star Trek'' lived on in other ways, and continued to play a part in Nichols' life. She again provided the voice of Uhura in ''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series]]''; in one episode, \"The Lorelei Signal\", Uhura assumes command of the ''Enterprise''.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Mangels|first=Andy|date=Summer 2018|title=Star Trek: The Animated Series|magazine=RetroFan|issue=1|pages=25\u201337|publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]]}}</ref> Nichols noted in her autobiography her frustration that this never happened on the original series. Nichols has co-starred in six ''Star Trek'' films, the last one being ''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]''.\n\n=== Other acting roles ===\n[[File:NichelleNicholsHWOFSept2012.jpg|thumb|right|Nichols in September 2012.]]\nIn 1994, Nichols published her autobiography ''Beyond Uhura: Star Trek and Other Memories''. In it, she claimed that the role of Peggy Fair in the television series ''[[Mannix]]'' was offered to her during the final season of ''Star Trek'', but producer Gene Roddenberry refused to release her from her contract. Between the end of the original series and the ''Star Trek'' animated series and feature films, Nichols appeared in small television and film roles. She briefly appeared as a secretary in ''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]'' (1967), and portrayed a foul-mouthed madam in ''[[Truck Turner]]'' (1974) opposite [[Isaac Hayes]], her only appearance in a [[blaxploitation]] film.\n\nNichols appeared in animated form as one of [[Al Gore]]'s Vice Presidential Action Rangers in the \"[[Anthology of Interest I]]\" episode of ''[[Futurama]]'', and she provided the voice of her own head in a glass jar in the episode \"[[Where No Fan Has Gone Before]]\". She voiced the recurring role of [[Elisa Maza]]'s mother Diane Maza in the animated series ''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]'', and played Thoth-Kopeira in an episode of ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''. In 2004, she provided the voice for herself in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Simple Simpson]]\". In the comedy film ''[[Snow Dogs]]'' (2002), Nichols appeared as the mother of the male lead, played by [[Cuba Gooding Jr]]. In 2006, she appeared as the title character in the film ''[[Lady Magdalene's]]'', the madam of a legal Nevada brothel in tax default. She also served as executive producer and choreographer, and sang three songs in the film, two of which she composed. In addition to her acting skills, Nichols is an accomplished dancer and singer. She has twice been nominated for the Chicago theatrical [[Sarah Siddons Award]] for Best Actress. The first nomination was for her portrayal of Hazel Sharpe in ''Kicks and Co.''; the second for her performance in ''[[The Blacks (play)|The Blacks]]''.\n\nNichols played a recurring role on the second season of the NBC drama ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. Her first appearance was on the episode \"[[Kindred (Heroes)|Kindred]]\", which aired October 8, 2007. She portrayed Nana Dawson, the matriarch of a New Orleans family financially and personally devastated by [[Hurricane Katrina]], who cares for her orphaned grandchildren and her great-nephew, series regular [[Micah Sanders]]. In 2008, Nichols starred in the film ''The Torturer'', playing the role of a psychiatrist. In 2009, she joined the cast of ''The Cabonauts'', a sci-fi musical comedy that debuted on the Internet. Playing CJ, the CEO of the Cabonauts Inc, Nichols is also featured singing and dancing. On August 30, 2016, she was introduced as the aging mother of Neil Winters on the long-standing soap opera ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''. She received her first [[Daytime Emmy]] nomination in the \"[[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Guest Performer in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Performer in a Drama Series]]\" category for this role March 22, 2017.<ref name=\"NATAS 2017\">{{Cite web|url=http://cdn.emmyonline.org/day_44th_nominations_v02.pdf|title=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences Announces Nominations For The 44th Annual Daytime Emmy\u00ae Awards|date=2017-03-22|website=[[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]|access-date=2017-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nNichols has released two music albums. ''Down to Earth'' is a collection of standards released in 1967, during the original run of ''Star Trek''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/down-to-earth-mw0000475901|title=Down to Earth|first=Lindsay|last=Planer|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> ''Out of This World'', released in 1991, is more rock oriented and is themed around ''Star Trek'' and space exploration.\n\nAs mentioned earlier, she sang with the Duke Ellington Orchestra and Lionel Hampton. In her role as Lieutenant Uhura on Star Trek, she sang two songs in the episode \"[[Charlie X]]\".\n\n== Work with NASA ==\n[[File:Space shuttle enterprise star trek-cropcast.jpg|upright=1.7|thumb|Nichols (fourth from the left) with most of the cast of ''Star Trek'' visiting the [[Space Shuttle Enterprise]] at the [[Rockwell International]] plant at [[Palmdale, California]], USA, 1976.]]\nAfter the cancellation of ''Star Trek'', Nichols volunteered her time in a special project with [[NASA]] to recruit minority and female personnel for the space agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grin.hq.nasa.gov/ABSTRACTS/GPN-2004-00017.html|title=Nichelle Nichols, NASA Recruiter|website=Great Images In NASA|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091222042250/http://grin.hq.nasa.gov/ABSTRACTS/GPN-2004-00017.html|archive-date=2009-12-22}}</ref> She began this work by making an affiliation between NASA and a company which she helped to run, Women in Motion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2011/02/02/to-boldly-go/|title=To boldly go: Groundbreaking actress Nichelle Nichols continues to expand her horizons|last=Prafder|first=Erika|date=2011-02-02|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://bitchmagazine.org/post/where-no-woman-has-gone-before-an-actress-spotlight-on-nichelle-nichols|title=Where No Woman Has Gone Before: An Actress Spotlight on Nichelle Nichols|date=2009-07-29|magazine=[[Bitch (magazine)|Bitch]]|access-date=2014-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006131851/http://bitchmagazine.org/post/where-no-woman-has-gone-before-an-actress-spotlight-on-nichelle-nichols|archive-date=2014-10-06|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nywici.org/features/blogs/aloud/black-history-month-profile-nichelle-nichols|title=Black History Month Profile: Nichelle Nichols|first=Linda|last=Levi|date=2011-02-21|website=New York Women In Communications|access-date=2014-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009063639/http://www.nywici.org/features/blogs/aloud/black-history-month-profile-nichelle-nichols#|archive-date=2011-10-09|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nss\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nss.org/about/bios/nichols.html|title=Nichelle Nichols, National Space Society Board of Governors|website=[[National Space Society]]|access-date=2014-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Nichelle_Nichols.aspx|title=Nichelle Nichols|website=[[Encyclopedia.com]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\"smithsonian\">{{Cite magazine|url=http://blogs.smithsonianmag.com/aroundthemall/2011/06/q-a-nichelle-nichols-aka-lt-uhura-and-nasa/|title=Q & A: Nichelle Nichols, AKA Lt. Uhura, and NASA|last=Childs|first=Arcynta Ali|date=2011-06-23|magazine=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nThe program was a success. Among those recruited were Dr. [[Sally Ride]], the first American female astronaut, and [[United States Air Force]] Colonel [[Guion Bluford]], the first African-American astronaut, as well as Dr. [[Judith Resnik]] and Dr. [[Ronald McNair]], who both flew successful missions during the [[Space Shuttle program]] before their deaths in the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' disaster]] on January 28, 1986. Recruits also included [[Charles Bolden]], the former [[NASA administrator]] and veteran of four shuttle missions, Frederick D. Gregory, former deputy administrator and a veteran of three shuttle missions and Lori Garver, former deputy administrator. An enthusiastic advocate of space exploration, Nichols has served since the mid-1980s on the [[Board of Governors|board of governors]] of the [[National Space Society]], a nonprofit, educational [[space advocacy]] organization founded by Dr. [[Wernher von Braun]].<ref name=\"nss\"/>\n\nIn late 2015, Nichols flew aboard NASA's Stratospheric Observatory for Infrared Astronomy (SOFIA) [[Boeing 747SP]], which analyzed the atmospheres of [[Mars]] and [[Saturn]] on an eight-hour, high-altitude mission. She was also a special guest at the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] in [[Pasadena, California]], on July 17, 1976, to view the [[Viking 1]] soft landing on Mars. Along with the other cast members from the original ''Star Trek'' series, she attended the christening of the first space shuttle, ''[[Space Shuttle Enterprise|Enterprise]]'', at the [[North American Rockwell]] assembly facility in [[Palmdale, California]]. On {{Date|2010-07-14|MDY}}, she toured the space shuttle simulator and Mission Control at the Johnson Space Center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twitpic.com/25brxs|title=Nichelle Nicholls, Star Trek's Uhura, in the Shuttle Simulator at NASA at Houston|date=2010-07-14|website=[[TwitPic]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nNichols' younger brother, Thomas, was a member of the [[Heaven's Gate (cult)|Heaven's Gate]] cult. He died on March 26, 1997 in the cult's [[mass suicide]] that purposely coincided with the passing of the [[Comet Hale-Bopp|Hale-Bopp comet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reocities.com/Hollywood/6952/nichols.htm|title=Nichelle Nichols' Connection to the Heaven's Gate Cult Tragedy|website=[[Reocities]]|access-date=2014-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624125458/http://www.reocities.com/Hollywood/6952/nichols.htm|archive-date=2013-06-24|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A member for 20 years, he frequently identified himself as Nichelle's brother in promotional materials released by the cult.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/heavens-gate-the-sequel-2147951|title=Heaven's Gate: The Sequel|last=Bearman|first=Joshuah|authorlink= Joshuah Bearman|date=2007-03-21|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9703/28/mass.suicide.pm/|title=Some members of suicide cult castrated|date=1997-03-28|work=CNN|access-date=2010-05-20|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19990222131949/http://www.cnn.com/US/9703/28/mass.suicide.pm/|archive-date=1999-02-22}}</ref>\n\nIn her autobiography, Nichols stated that she was romantically involved with ''Star Trek'' creator [[Gene Roddenberry]] for a few years in the 1960s. She said the affair ended well before ''Star Trek'' began, when she and Roddenberry realized he was in love with [[Majel Barrett|Majel Hudec]], who was an acquaintance of Nichols, and who went on to have a regular supporting role as nurse [[Christine Chapel]] on ''Star Trek''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Beyond Uhura|last=Nichols|first=Nichelle|date=October 1994|publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]|isbn=9780399139932|location=New York|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beyonduhurastart00nich}}</ref> When Roddenberry's health was fading, Nichols co-wrote a song for him, entitled \"Gene\", which she sang at his funeral.\n\nNichols has married twice, first to dancer Foster Johnson (1917\u20131981). They were married in 1951 and divorced that same year. Johnson and Nichols had one child together, [[Kyle Johnson (actor)|Kyle Johnson]], who was born August 14, 1951. She married Duke Mondy in 1968. They were divorced in 1972.\n\nOn {{Date|2012-02-29|MDY}}, Nichols met with President [[Barack Obama]] in the [[Oval Office]]. She later tweeted about the meeting, \"Months ago, Pres Obama was quoted as saying that he'd had a crush on me when he was younger,\" Nichols also wrote. \"I asked about that and he proudly confirmed it! President Obama also confirmed for me that he was definitely a Trekker! How wonderful is that?!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2012/04/obama-gives-vulcan-salute-with-lt-uhura/1#.WJG_tYVOLkk|title=Obama gives Vulcan salute with Lt. Uhura|first=David|last=Jackson|date=2012-04-05|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2015, Nichols' booking agency announced that she had suffered a mild stroke at her [[Los Angeles]] home and had been admitted to a Los Angeles-area hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-33018975|title=Nichelle Nichols, Star Trek's Lt Uhura, suffers stroke|date=2015-06-05|website=BBC News|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/star-trek-star-nichelle-nichols-hospitalized/ar-BBkHsc3|title='Star Trek' Star Nichelle Nichols Hospitalized|first=Erin|last=Whitney|date=2015-06-05|website=MSN.com|access-date=2019-08-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054211/http://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/star-trek-star-nichelle-nichols-hospitalized/ar-BBkHsc3|archive-date=2016-03-04}}</ref> A [[magnetic resonance imaging]] (MRI) scan revealed a small stroke had occurred, and she began inpatient therapy on {{Date|2015-06-05|MDY}}.\n\nNichols was diagnosed with dementia sometime in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/959320/star-trek-s-nichelle-nichols-diagnosed-with-dementia|title=Star Trek's Nichelle Nichols Diagnosed With Dementia|last=Cohen|first=Jess|date=2018-04-10|website=[[E!|E! Online]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> She subsequently announced her retirement from convention appearances, with a farewell event to be held in Burbank in May 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trekmovie.com/2019/05/05/nichelle-nichols-announces-farewell-tour-convention-and-documentary/|title=Nichelle Nichols Announces Farewell Tour, Convention And Documentary|last=Pascale|first=Anthony|date=2018-05-19|website=TrekMovie.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nNichols is an honorary member of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] sorority. [[Robert A. Heinlein]] in part dedicated his novel ''[[Friday (novel)|Friday]]'' (1982) to her.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Heinlein|first=Robert A.|authorlink=Robert A. Heinlein|title=Friday|publisher=New England Library|year=1984|isbn=978-0-450-05549-2}}</ref> On June 8, 2010, Nichols received an [[honorary degree]] from [[Los Angeles Mission College]].\n\nAsteroid [[68410 Nichols]] is named in her honor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=68410|title=68410 Nichols (2001 QB154)|last=Chamberlin|first=Alan|date=2005-09-26|website=JPL Small-Body Database Browser|access-date=2016-11-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Nichols was awarded a [[Goldene Kamera]] for {{Lang|de|Kultstar des Jahrhunderts}} ({{Lang-en|Cult Star of the Century}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenekamera.de/preisverleihung/chronik-fakten/article207117753/GOLDENE-KAMERA-1999-34-Verleihung.html|title=Goldene Kamera 1999 - 34. Verleihung|website=Goldene Kamera 1999|url-status=live|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she received [[The Life Career Award]], from the [[Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films]] and it was presented as part of the [[42nd Saturn Awards]] ceremony.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1959\n|''[[Porgy and Bess (film)|Porgy and Bess]]''\n|Dancer (uncredited)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1966\n|''[[Tarzan's Deadly Silence]]''\n|Ruana\n|-\n|''[[Made in Paris]]''\n|Buyer at Salon\n|-\n|''[[Mister Buddwing]]''\n|Dice Player #3\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]''\n|Jenny Ribbock\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[Truck Turner]]''\n|Dorinda\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Uhura\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan]]''\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1986\n|''[[Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home]]''\n|-\n|''[[The Supernaturals (horror film)|The Supernaturals]]''\n|Sgt. Leona Hawkins\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Star Trek V: The Final Frontier]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Uhura\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]''\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[The Adventures of Captain Zoom in Outer Space]]''\n|High Priestess of Pangea\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Snow Dogs]]''\n|Amelia Brooks\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Surge of Power: The Stuff of Heroes]]''\n|Oman\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Are We There Yet? (film)|Are We There Yet?]]''\n|Miss Mable\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2008\n|''[[Lady Magdalene's]]''\n|Lady Magdalene{{\\}}Maggie\n|-\n|''[[Tru Loved]]''\n|Grandmother\n|-\n|''The Torturer''\n|Doc\n|-\n|2012\n|''This Bitter Earth''\n|Clara Watkins\n|-\n|2016\n|''Renegades''\n|Grace Jemison\n|-\n|2017\n|''The Order''\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''American Nightmares''\n|Mystic Woman\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television and video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1964\n|''[[The Lieutenant]]''\n|Norma Bartlett\n|\"[[To Set It Right]]\"\n|-\n|1966\u20131969\n|''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]''\n|Uhura\n|\n|-\n|1970\n|''[[Insight (TV series)|Insight]]''\n|Ellie\n|\"Old King Cole\"\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series]]''\n|Uhura{{\\}}Additional voices\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''Antony and Cleopatra''\n|Charmian \u2013 Maid of Honour\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''Star Trek: 25th Anniversary Enhanced''\n|Uhura\n|Video game\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1994\n|''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]''\n|Diane Maza\n|4 episodes\n|-\n|''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''\n|Thoth-Khepera\n|\"Avatar\"\n|-\n|''[[Star Trek: Judgment Rites]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Uhura\n|Video game\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''\n|\"[[Trials and Tribble-ations]]\" (archive footage)\n|-\n|2000\u20132002\n|''[[Futurama]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Herself\n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Simpsons]]''\n|\"[[Simple Simpson]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2007\n|''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''\n|Nana Dawson\n|\"[[Kindred (Heroes)|Kindred]]\"\n|-\n|''[[Star Trek: Of Gods and Men]]''\n|Uhura\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''The Cabonauts''\n|CJ\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Scooby-Doo! Curse of the Lake Monster]]''\n|Senator\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Young and the Restless]]''\n|Lucinda<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/07/26/nichelle-nichols-the-young-and-the-restless-cast/|title=Y&R Beams Up Star Trek Alumna Nichelle Nichols for 'Emotional' Role|last=Swift|first=Andy|date=2016-07-26|website=[[TVLine]]|access-date=2016-11-22}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|''[[Downward Dog (TV series)|Downward Dog]]''\n|Deejay Devine\n|\n|-\n|''[[Sharknado 5: Global Swarming]]''\n|Starr\n|\n|}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Publisher\n!Date\n!ISBN\n!Notes\n|-\n|''Beyond Uhura''\n|[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]]\n|{{Dts|1994|10|19}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-399-13993-1}}\n|\n|-\n|''Saturn's Child''\n|[[Penguin Random House|Penguin]]\n|{{Dts|1995|10|17}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-399-14113-8}}\n|with [[Margaret Wander Bonanno]]\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction|Television}}\n*''[[Star Trek]]''\n* [[Kirk and Uhura's kiss]]\n* [[Space Shuttle Enterprise|Space Shuttle ''Enterprise'']]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|629675}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{AllMovie name|52569}}\n* {{Isfdb name|id=861|name=Nichelle Nichols}}\n* {{Emmytvlegends name|nichelle-nichols}}\n\n{{The Life Career Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nichols, Nichelle}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Star Trek fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Robbins, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:People with dementia]]\n", "name_user": "Smbil58", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "ur